# Vendored from https://github.com/eyereasoner/eye/blob/master/reasoning/good-cobbler/
# (cobbler.n3 facts + cobbler-query.n3 rule combined). Unmodified besides
# combining the two upstream files.
#
# BLOCKED (see manifest.json "status": "ignored"): both the fact and the
# rule pattern use an RDF list term, `(:good :Cobbler)` / `(:good ?Y)`. This
# crate represents every list term as an opaque synthetic blank-node id
# (see triples.rs's LIST_REGISTRY design note) assigned fresh at parse time;
# `TripleIndex::query` (tripleindex.rs) only ever compares such ids for exact
# equality, it does no structural/element-wise list-pattern unification. So
# a rule pattern list containing a variable, like `(:good ?Y)`, can never
# match a *different*, separately-parsed ground list term like
# `(:good :Cobbler)` even though they're structurally compatible -- the two
# get distinct registry ids. General list-pattern unification (as opposed to
# the explicit list built-ins list:in/length/append/sum/concat, which
# dereference a list's members procedurally and do work) is out of scope.
@prefix : <https://eyereasoner.github.io/ns#>.

:joe :is (:good :Cobbler).

{
    ?X :is (:good ?Y).
} => {
    ?X :is (:good ?Y).
}.
